BEIJING, Dec. 20 (Xinhua) -- A new draft revision to China's Law on Scientific and Technological Progress, proposing additional provisions to boost sci-tech innovation, is being considered by lawmakers. The new draft was submitted to the Standing Committee of the National People's Congress, China's top legislature, for a second reading on Monday. It calls on R&D institutions, institutions of higher education and enterprises to offer incentive measures such as dividends and stock rights. According to the draft, efforts should be made to streamline management procedures to cut excessive administrative paperwork for sci-tech professionals. Provisions on issues such as boosting the cultivation of talent in strategic sci-tech domains, allocating more resources to basic research and diversifying financing channels for sci-tech enterprises, were also introduced in the new draft. Enditem 